The paper deals with evolutionary multiobjective optimization, which is a subfield of machine learning and optimization. Specifically, it focuses on the behavior of different scalarizing functions and their parameters, which are commonly used in multiobjective optimization algorithms. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). However, the paper also discusses the difficulty of the single scalarized problems in terms of the search ability of a (1+lambda)-EA on biobjective NK-landscapes, which falls under cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Additionally, the paper uses set-based performance measures, which are commonly used in machine learning and optimization, and thus could also be classified under cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). Finally, the paper investigates the correlation between the opening angle of the scalarizing function's underlying contour lines and the position of the final solution in the objective space, which could be considered as a software engineering aspect and thus could also be classified under cs.SE (Software Engineering).
